  footnotes: []
english:
  title: 'Village Life: A Moment Observed'
  author: Byeon Gye-ryang
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Before layered peaks, the village stands in solitude.
    A few mulberry trees on two acres of field.
    Gathering herbs, I wander the forest floor,
    Drying books, I drowse beneath the sun.
    When clouds drift from the river-sky, I see returning geese,
    When moonlight brightens the mountain bamboo, I hear the cuckoo's call.
    Between two places, how endless the yearning—
    I compose this poem anew to send to you.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The 'two places' likely refers to the poet's divided loyalty or affection between two locations—possibly his hometown and current residence, or between the life of seclusion and the world beyond.
  - key: ''
    value: The cuckoo (杜鵑, dujonge) traditionally symbolizes longing and melancholy in East Asian poetry, complementing the theme of separation.
  - key: ''
    value: The juxtaposition of humble rural tasks—gathering herbs and drying books—with celestial imagery suggests the poet's attempt to find spiritual meaning in simple village life.
